Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Barbados. The Barbadian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. All non-resident British nationals currently in Barbados are strongly encouraged to contact their airline or tour operator, to review options and consider leaving as soon as practicably possible. See Health
The Government of Barbados has announced that anyone arriving in Barbados with a travel history from Hubei Province (China), Iran, Italy and South Korea will be subject to a 14 day quarantine. Individuals who have visited other parts of China in the past 14 days will be screened and if necessary, also placed in quarantine. The Government of Barbados is also advising residents of Barbados against all non-essential travel to Italy.
The Barbados Ministry of Health and Wellness has a coronavirus hotline staffed by public health officers 24 hours a day on +1 246 536 4500. The Government has announced that all public gatherings such as sporting and cultural events or any event that attracts crowds will be restricted to 100 persons. Visits by members of the public to all public and private geriatric institutions have been suspended until further notice
Most visits to Barbados are trouble free, but there have been incidents of crime including armed robbery and sexual assault. See Crime
The hurricane season normally runs from June to November. You should monitor local and international weather updates from the US National Hurricane Centre and follow the advice of local authorities, including any evacuation orders. See Natural disasters
UK health authorities have classified Barbados as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For more information and advice, visit the website of the National Travel Health Network and Centre website.
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in Barbados, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
The Overseas Business Risk service offers information and advice for British companies operating overseas on how to manage political, economic, and business security-related risks.
The UK-Barbados reciprocal healthcare agreement was terminated in October 2016. See Health
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
